eturn the index (0-indexed) of the valid point with the smallest Manhattan distance from your current location. If there are multiple, return the valid point with the smallest index. If there are no valid points, return -1.\nThe Manhattan distance between two points (x1, y1) and (x2, y2) is abs(x1 - x2) + abs(y1 - y2).\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: x = 3, y = 4, points = [[1,2],[3,1],[2,4],[2,3],[4,4]]\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: Of all the points, only [3,1], [2,4] and [4,4] are valid. Of the valid points, [2,4] and [4,4] have the smallest Manhattan distance from your current location, with a distance of 1. [2,4] has the smallest index, so return 2.\nExample 2:\n\nInput: x = 3, y = 4, points = [[3,4]]\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: The answer is allowed to be on the same location as your current location.\nExample 3:\n\nInput: x = 3, y = 4, points = [[2,3]]\nOutput: -1\nExplanation: There are no valid points.\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= points.length <= 104\npoints[i].length == 2\n1 <= x, y, ai, bi <= 104\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def nearestValidPoint(self, x: int, y: int, points: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def nearestValidPoint(self, x: int, y: int, points: List[List[int]]) -> int:\n        min_distance = float('inf')\n        min_index = -1\n        \n        for index, (px, py) in enumerate(points):\n            if px == x or py == y:  # Check if the point is valid\n                distance = abs(x - px) + abs(y - py)\n                if distance < min_distance:\n                    min_distance = distance\n                    min_index = index\n        \n        return min_index\n```\n\nThis solution iterates through each point in the `points` list, checking if the point is valid by comparing its x or y coordinate with the given location (x, y). If the point is valid, it calculates the Manhattan distance and updates the minimum distance and index if the current distance is smaller. If multiple points have the same minimum distance, the index of the first one encountered is returned. If no valid points are found, it returns -1.", "estimated_date": 1614470400000}